ernments may actually afford new venues for commodity development and exchange. Presenting prominent case studies of communication law and policy, corporate hacks, and key players in the global cybersecurity market, the book proposes a political economic model of new markets for software vulnerabilities and exploits, and clearly illustrates the social functions of hacking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHackers. 0aHackingxPolitical aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  acase studies.  acommodity development.  acommunication law.  acompetitive advantage.  acorporations.  acritical communication.  acybersecurity.  adigital capitalism.  aeuropean union.  aeveryday use of technology.  afraud.  agovernment agencies.  agovernment entities.  agovernments.  ahackers.  aidentity theft.  ainvasive software.  alone wolf.  amanaging risk.  amedia studies.  apolitical economic model.  asocial change.  atrusted systems.  aunited states.1 aMcCourt, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520971653zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520971653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520971653.jpg  a978-3-11-066